In [13]:
# Create the optimization variables.
F = cp.Variable((len(C),1))
 
# set the contraints
nu = np.zeros((len(B),1))
nu[0]= ans_1c
nu[-1]=-ans_1c
constraints = [F<=C, F>=0, B*F == nu]

#Create the problem and objective
obj = cp.Minimize((cp.sum(cp.multiply(C,cp.multiply(l,cp.inv_pos(1-cp.multiply(F, cp.inv_pos(C)))))-cp.multiply(l,C))))
prob = cp.Problem(obj, constraints)

# Solve the problem using the MOSEK solver
prob.solve()

# Create the cariables needed when creating the tolls
F_star = np.array(list(F_opt2.values())).reshape((28, 1))
we = cp.multiply(F_star,cp.multiply(cp.multiply(C,l),cp.inv_pos(cp.power(C-F_star,2))))
w_star = we #- l

# Create the optimization variables.
F = cp.Variable((len(C),1))

# set contraints
nu = np.zeros((len(B),1))
nu[0]= ans_1c
nu[-1]=-ans_1c
constraints = [F<=C, F>=0, B*F == nu]

# Create the problem and objective
cost = cp.Minimize(cp.sum(cp.multiply(cp.multiply(C,l),(cp.log(C)-cp.log(C-F))) + cp.multiply(F,w_star) - cp.multiply(l,F)))
prob = cp.Problem(cost, constraints)
# Solve the problem using the MOSEK solver
prob.solve()

# -------------------- HELPERS --------------------------------
# HELPER 1
def num(i,t,node_colors,loc_color,cost_function,mu):
    c_vector = []
    for c_i in node_colors:
        if cost_function == 1:
            c_vector.append(c(loc_color,c_i))
        else:
            c_vector.append(c2(loc_color,c_i))
    sigma = np.sum(c_vector)
    return np.exp(-t*sigma/mu)

#HELPER 2
def den(i,t,node_colors, potential_colors,cost_function,mu):
    sigma = 0
    for loc_color in potential_colors:
        sigma = sigma + num(i,t,node_colors,loc_color,cost_function,mu)
    return sigma

#HELPER 3
def prop_color(i,t,node_colors,color,potential_colors,cost_function,mu):
    numerator = num(i,t,node_colors,color,cost_function,mu) 
    denominator = den(i,t,node_colors,potential_colors,cost_function,mu)
    return numerator/denominator

# ---------- These are the functions defined in the Handin --------------
def propability_distribution(i,t,node_colors,potential_colors,cost_function,mu):
    prob_dist = {}
    for pot_c in potential_colors:
        prob_dist[pot_c] = prop_color(i,t,node_colors,pot_c,potential_colors,cost_function,mu)
    return prob_dist

# Cost function
def c(s,X_t):
    if s == X_t:
        return 1
    else:
        return 0

# Potential Function 
def potential_function(G, node_colors):
    sigma = 0
    nodes = list(G.nodes())
    W = nx.adjacency_matrix(G)
    for n in nodes:
        other_nodes = nodes.copy()
        other_nodes.remove(n)
        for o_n in other_nodes:
            sigma = sigma + W[n-1,o_n-1] *c(node_colors[n-1],node_colors[o_n-1])
        #print(other_nodes)
        
    return sigma/2

# Learning dynamics simulation
def learning_dynamics_simulation(G, node_colors,potential_colors,cost_function=1,mu=100, t_limit = 500):
    min_U = 10000 # Random high valued Integer 
    min_index = -1
    node_colors_loc = node_colors.copy()
    sim = [node_colors]
    x = []
    U = potential_function(G, node_colors_loc)
    t = 0
    while U != 0:
        t = t+1
        i = int((rand.random()*len(node_colors))+1)
        prob_dist = propability_distribution(i,t,node_colors_loc,potential_colors,cost_function,mu)
        prob_dist_colors = list(prob_dist.keys())
        prob_dist_values = list(prob_dist.values())
        node_colors_loc[i-1] = np.random.choice(prob_dist_colors, p=prob_dist_values)
        sim.append(node_colors_loc.copy())
        U = potential_function(G, node_colors_loc)
        if U < min_U:
            min_index = t
            min_U = U
            #print(min_index)
            #print(U)
        x.append(U)
        if t == t_limit:
            print('Timelimit reached, at best reached potential ' + str(min_U) + ' at time ' + str(min_index))
            break
    if t != t_limit:
        print('Simulation Successful. t = ' + str(t) + ' when potential = 0')
    plt.figure(1,figsize=(10,5))
    plt.plot(x)
    plt.title('Potential over time')
    plt.xlabel('Time')
    plt.ylabel('U')
    plt.show
    return node_colors_loc, sim, min_index

Simulation with mu = t/1000¶

Simulation Successful. t = 123 when potential = 0

By studying the potential over time for different mu values we cannot make any conclusion regarding the convergence rate for the different simulations. I saw that for mu = t, the algorithms were not robust enough and often genreated nan in the probabilites as soon as t went over 150. (That is why I set the t-limit lower for this simulation. We will do 10 simulations using three different mus to see if there is a difference between run-time before potential = 0.

In [194]:
# WARNING: LONG RUN TIME ~ 10 min. Might want to comment of the plots in the function before running as well... 
# Simulating the run_time 150 times when mu = 100 and when mu = 1000.
mus = [100, 1000]
d = {}
i = 1
for mu in mus:
    node_colors_end, sim, min_index = learning_dynamics_simulation(G, node_color,potential_colors,t_limit = 2000,mu=mu)
    d[mu] = [len(sim)]
    for i in range(150):
        node_colors_end, sim, min_index = learning_dynamics_simulation(G, node_color,potential_colors,t_limit = 2000,mu=mu)
        d[mu].append(len(sim))
In [195]:
# Calculates the confidence_interval and the mean for some data
def confidence_interval(data, confidence=0.95):
    data_array = 1.0 * np.array(data)
    m = np.mean(data_array), 
    std = scipy.stats.sem(data_array)
    conf_interval = std * scipy.stats.t.ppf((1 + confidence) / 2., len(data_array)-1)
    return m, m-conf_interval, m+conf_interval

((781.7682119205298,), array([690.80991321]), array([872.72651063]))

We can conclude that there is a significant difference between the mean run time when mu = t/100 and when mu = t/1000. We also saw that using to mu = t/10 and mu =1 generated NaN probabilites after t ~ 1500 and t ~ 150.

This leaves us to conclude that there is a trade off between robusness and speed of convergence. When setting a denominator in mu that is larger we get a more robust simulation, however it takes us longer to reach a state in which the potential is 0.

In [204]:
# Cost function 2
def c2(s,X_t):
    distance = find_distance(s,X_t)
    if distance == 0:
        return 2
    elif distance == 1:
        return 1
    else:
        return 0

# Distance between two states    
def find_distance(S,X_t):
    distance = np.absolute(domain_mapping[S] - domain_mapping[X_t])
    return distance

As we can see from the potential over time plots above, the potential stagnates around t = 200 and moves in the range 18-22. In order to get a better solution, I personally would use a different method:

  • Start by assigning all the nodes a random color, not the same ones

  • Divide the graph into its components, and run the simulations locally on each componant
